00:24:02,034 --> 00:24:04,515
and really does make it feel like what I call an EP,

570
00:24:04,535 --> 00:24:06,136
which would be an extended play in music,

571
00:24:06,216 --> 00:24:08,637
but, you know, for our intents and purposes,

572
00:24:08,717 --> 00:24:10,498
it's another video game mixtape.

573
00:24:11,278 --> 00:24:14,019
And a lot of these ideas stem from this guy,

574
00:24:14,059 --> 00:24:16,340
or at least I take inspiration from this guy.

575
00:24:16,380 --> 00:24:18,421
This is Gunpei Yokoi, who designed...

576
00:24:18,997 --> 00:24:22,759
the Game Boy and the Virtual Boy and he's a, working for, worked for Nintendo,

577
00:24:22,779 --> 00:24:25,480
a late, late designer, but, um,

578
00:24:26,420 --> 00:24:29,762
he talked about lateral thinking with withered technology, and that's this idea

579
00:24:29,802 --> 00:24:32,783
that we have all this technology available to us now, it's cheap, it's

580
00:24:32,823 --> 00:24:36,064
accessible, we all know how to use Unity, there's lots of documentation,

581
00:24:36,084 --> 00:24:39,246
uh, our players, they know how to play screen-based games, they know how to play

582
00:24:39,266 --> 00:24:42,347
games on their phone, uh, so if everything's so accessible

583
00:24:42,847 --> 00:24:45,388
and affordable, then we should think laterally of what...

584
00:24:45,749 --> 00:24:46,929
kind of stories you want to tell,

585
00:24:46,969 --> 00:24:48,890
let's use it to tell stories in innovative

586
00:24:48,931 --> 00:24:50,752
and new ways that people haven't done yet

587
00:24:50,792 --> 00:24:52,573
rather than always chasing the cutting edge.

588
00:24:52,613 --> 00:24:54,594
Everyone's gonna always chase after that.

589
00:24:54,654 --> 00:24:56,495
Did you saw the line for the VR talk next door?

590
00:24:56,515 --> 00:24:58,496
It's like down over to the bathroom,

591
00:24:58,536 --> 00:25:00,618
but I'm very grateful for all of you to be here with me.

592
00:25:01,638 --> 00:25:04,760
So VR is super expensive for developers

593
00:25:04,840 --> 00:25:06,501
as well as for consumers.

594
00:25:06,561 --> 00:25:09,883
So if you stick to withered technology,

595
00:25:10,764 --> 00:25:12,285
we can make things that are certainly more accessible

596
00:25:12,345 --> 00:25:13,626
to the larger group of people.

597
00:25:14,864 --> 00:25:17,494
So to wrap up, a couple of keys to video game mixtapes.

598
00:25:18,498 --> 00:25:20,064
One is to embrace the creative freedom.

599
00:25:21,397 --> 00:25:23,177
So as you make it, you can just make whatever you want.

600
00:25:23,197 --> 00:25:25,978
Just make a bunch of little pieces and you know,

601
00:25:25,998 --> 00:25:27,858
you can figure out what it's going to be as you make them.

602
00:25:27,878 --> 00:25:30,719
You might notice trends in your art or what you're interested in.

603
00:25:31,179 --> 00:25:32,780
And you'll figure out the order as you make it.

604
00:25:33,160 --> 00:25:35,100
Some of these seem like they're well planned out, but it's not.

605
00:25:35,140 --> 00:25:37,001
I just made a bunch of things that I thought would be kind of cool

606
00:25:37,081 --> 00:25:39,441
and then I figured out later how can we start piecing them together

607
00:25:39,461 --> 00:25:41,702
because I had to show some work to my class.

608
00:25:41,802 --> 00:25:42,802
Okay, I have three.

609
00:25:42,842 --> 00:25:45,843
Let's just piece them together and come up with a retro script,

610
00:25:45,883 --> 00:25:47,163
a story as to why.

611
00:25:48,064 --> 00:25:50,828
But just remember that the players are going to figure out, or they're going to make up

612
00:25:50,848 --> 00:25:53,993
the connections for you so you don't have to be explicit with it.

613
00:25:54,133 --> 00:25:57,278
And it's the diversity of experiences is what's really going to enhance the mix.

614
00:25:59,260 --> 00:26:01,141
Two is to keep it flexible and modular.

615
00:26:01,201 --> 00:26:03,343
The beauty about working in this way is if,

616
00:26:03,563 --> 00:26:05,945
like for me, I got like way better every couple months

617
00:26:05,965 --> 00:26:07,086
that I was working on this project,

618
00:26:07,106 --> 00:26:08,927
so I could just quarantine all the bad code.

619
00:26:08,987 --> 00:26:10,589
Like, oh my God, why did I code it this way?

620
00:26:10,929 --> 00:26:12,770
Well, it works, so we'll just put that in the corner

621
00:26:12,810 --> 00:26:13,771
and not touch it anymore,

622
00:26:13,811 --> 00:26:15,372
not build any systems on top of that.

623
00:26:15,833 --> 00:26:17,694
But, you know, we have this piece that works,

624
00:26:18,014 --> 00:26:19,816
and then we'll just make sure the next piece that we do,

625
00:26:19,896 --> 00:26:22,478
we're gonna code it and organize our files

626
00:26:22,518 --> 00:26:23,279
in a much better way.

627
00:26:24,389 --> 00:26:28,151
And if you make something cool later, it doesn't have to be a ton of work to implement it because

628
00:26:28,191 --> 00:26:31,093
it's a mix so you can just add in this cool thing afterwards.

629
00:26:32,173 --> 00:26:36,095
As well as like I mentioned earlier, it's a great way to get collaborators to work because

630
00:26:36,115 --> 00:26:39,357
you're building these small pieces and it's much more visible and tangible for them how

631
00:26:39,377 --> 00:26:39,997
they would fit in.

632
00:26:40,057 --> 00:26:43,359
Oh, I need you to make this art look better, I need you to do a song for this little piece,

633
00:26:43,399 --> 00:26:44,140
I need you to do...

634
00:26:45,839 --> 00:26:48,342
sound effects or code to make some of these things smooth and out.

635
00:26:48,362 --> 00:26:52,748
There's a lot that we can do, you know, to respect people's times,

636
00:26:52,888 --> 00:26:55,892
both for our fellow developers as well as for the players.

637
00:26:56,874 --> 00:26:59,597
Get in, do your thing, and get out. That's a big part of it, right?

638
00:26:59,617 --> 00:27:01,460
You don't want to just linger too long on one piece

639
00:27:01,520 --> 00:27:02,942
because someone might get bored or...

640
00:27:03,663 --> 00:27:05,984
you know, I think it's good to err on the side of caution because you could say, oh,

